    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is actually a superclass field in every <code>.class</code> file, including those that represent interfaces.</p>\n\n<p>For an interface it always points to <code>java.lang.Object</code>.  But that isn't used for anything.</p>\n\n<p>Another way to look at it is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>interface MyInterface {\n    // ...\n}\n\npublic myMethod(MyInterface param) {\n    Object obj = (Object) param;\n    // ...\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Here the cast <code>(Object) param</code> is always valid, which implies that every interface type is a subtype of <code>java.lang.Object</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 91502,
      "reputation" : 89455,
      "user_id" : 251173,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 86,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/23de335ea2208b179ece18bec0b2597f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Buhake Sindi",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/251173/buhake-sindi"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1305796592,
    "creation_date" : 1305796592,
    "answer_id" : 6056365,
    "question_id" : 6056124,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>That's because <code>employee e = ...</code> reads that there is a class that <strong>implements</strong> <code>employee</code>, and is assigned to variable <code>e</code>. Every class that implements an interface extends Object implicitly, hence when you do <code>e.equals(null)</code>, the language knows that you have a class that is a subtype of <code>employee</code>. </p>\n\n<p>The JVM will do runtime checking for your code (i.e. throw <code>NullPointerException</code>).</p>\n"
  }, {
