    "answer_id" : 6057181,
    "question_id" : 6056124,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>Object</code> is a supertype of any interface [1] </p>\n\n<p>However, an interface does not <code>implements</code>, <code>extends</code>, or, <em>\"inherit from\"</em> <code>Object</code>.</p>\n\n<p>JLS has a special clause to add <code>Object</code> methods into interfaces [2]</p>\n\n<p>[1] <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/docs/books/jls/third_edition/html/typesValues.html#4.10.2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://java.sun.com/docs/books/jls/third_edition/html/typesValues.html#4.10.2</a></p>\n\n<p>[2] <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/docs/books/jls/third_edition/html/interfaces.html#9.2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://java.sun.com/docs/books/jls/third_edition/html/interfaces.html#9.2</a></p>\n"
  }, {
